content: You'd be better served by an SSH app that gives you more configuration choices (multiple users with different root folders, ability to stop-start on your specific WiFi, etc.)

I have used two other FTP servers bundled with file managers on my old phone (moto G3) but when I tried them on my new phone (honor lite 9) I could not get them to work. However the WiFi Pro worked first time (using filezilla FTP client on my Linux PC) initially in FTP mode with instructions to switch to more secure Ftps mode, which also worked first time, after I remembered to change the address to ftps: ! Very impressed, especially at the low cost for the ad-free version.

This is a well-written app, but is oriented for manual operation only. It expects the user to be interacting with the server app.  Ideally, a server would be an autonomous service. That would enable unattended backup scripts to run from another system late at night, for example.   1) It has no "Start server with Android" option. Manually starting the server is always required.  2) While it can access the ExtSdCard, it cannot simultaneously provide access to the ExtSdCard and internal storage.  The FTP root folder has to be manually changed in the app. The Android filesystem root is not an option.  This means an FTP session cannot access both storage areas.  3) There is no tasker plugin for automation (Tasker would be able to auto-start the server if the plugin was provided).   I tried this for a couple days, but because of these shortcomings, I had to move on. I'm still looking for an FTP server app. I would re-install this app and give 5 star review if these capabilities are added.

I just transferred 11 music albums - almost exactly 1 gig - from my computer to my Galaxy Note 4 in about 6 minutes.  I would take off a half a star if I could only because I wish it allowed transfer directly to the external SD card.  I can read from it but not write to it.  But this might be an Android limitation as other ftp apps do the same thing.  Still, it's easy enough to move the files to the SD card using the Android file manager.  Only took about a minute to move those 11 albums.
